# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1932-detroit-wolves-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The **1919 Detroit Stars baseball team** competed in Negro league baseball during the 1919 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In their first year of competition, the Stars won the championship of independent western Negro league clubs.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] While the Seamhead website reports that the team compiled a record of 27–13, the "Game Log" below includes 44 wins based on 1919 games for which contemporaneous newspaper accounts have been located.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played their home games at Mack Park in Detroit with a handful of games also played at Navin Field.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was owned by Tenny Blount and led by player-manager Pete Hill who compiled a .396 batting average and .892 slugging percentage.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was established in 1919 by owner Tenny Blount (1873–1934), sometimes also known as "Teddy" Blount, with assistance from Rube Foster who owned the Chicago American Giants.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Blount was an Alabama native who moved to Detroit in 1913 and became a prominent "numbers man".
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In addition to the three Hall of Fame inductees, the Stars received strong performances from several other position players.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] First baseman Edgar Wesley, a left-handed hitter from Texas, compiled a .322 batting average and a .610 slugging percentage for the 1919 Stars.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In 146 at bats, he tallied eight home runs, 21 extra-base hits, and 43 RBIs.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Joe Hewitt, an infielder from Alabama, led the team with 153 at bats and ranked second with 36 runs scored and third with 36 hits.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Second baseman Frank Warfield, a Kentucky native, led the team with eight triples.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Sam Crawford was the team's leading pitcher, compiling a 10–4 record and 2.89 earned run average (ERA).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] John Donaldson also pitched for the Stars, compiling a 2.33 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Donaldson was regarded as one of the greatest pitchers of the era, appearing in approximately 700 games with over 400 wins and 5,000 strikeouts.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] He was voted a first-team member of the 1952 *Pittsburgh Courier* player-voted poll of the Negro leagues best players ever.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] During April and May, the Stars opened the season with a 13-game win streak, including victories over all-white semipro teams.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In late May, an all-white team from Wyandotte, Michigan recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Rudy Kallio to start a game against the Stars; the Stars scored eight runs off Kallio.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The local semipro champion, the Maxwells, lost two games to the Stars in the first half of the season, then recruited major league pitcher Ralph Comstock to start a July 13 games against the Stars.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] With Comstock pitching a strong game for the Maxwells, the Stars lost their first game to a white team by a 4–3 score.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played a total of six games with the Maxwells in 1919, winning three games and losing two.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars' principal rivalry for the western championship of Negro league baseball came from Rube Foster's Chicago American Giants.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Giants won two of three in a series played in Chicago in June.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] When the teams met for a series in Detroit in early July, the Stars won three games.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The also played a seven-game seriesin late July and early August that was billed as the championship series.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars won five games to take the championship.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] As noted in the "Game Log" below, the Stars also played multiple series with other Negro League teams, including the Cuban Stars, Dayton Marcos from Ohio, and the Hilldale Club from Pennsylvania.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In the last game of the season, the Murray All Stars recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Bernie Boland; Boland held the Stars scoreless.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The following batting and pitching statistics are drawn from the Seamheads web site which appear to be incomplete.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The **1920 Brooklyn Royal Giants baseball team** represented the Brooklyn Royal Giants as an independent during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team compiled a 13–7–2 (.636) record and won the Eastern independent championship.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] Nat Strong was the team's owner, and John Henry Lloyd was the manager.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team played its home games at Dexter Park in Queens.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team's leading pitchers were Harry Kenyon (3–1, 2.65 ERA) and Jesse Hubbard (3–2, 3.19 ERA, 41 strikeouts).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1920 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 51–19–2 record (45–15–2 in NNL games) and won the first NNL championship.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and manager.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at Schorling Park in Chicago.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] The **1920 Detroit Stars baseball team** competed in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] The Stars compiled a 37–27 record (.578) and finished in second place in the NNL behind the Chicago American Giants.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played their home games at Mack Park located on the east side of Detroit, about four miles from downtown, at the southeast corner of Fairview Ave. and Mack Ave.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] The team was owned by Tenny Blount and led by player-manager Pete Hill.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Center fielder Jimmie Lyons appeared in 59 games and led the team in most batting categories: batting average (.379), on-base percentage (.445), slugging percentage (.595), runs (64), hits (86), and stolen bases (21).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] His batting average, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage all ranked second in the NNL behind only Cristóbal Torriente.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Lyons also led the team with a 9.5 range factor, 92 outfield putouts, and 12 outfield assists.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] First baseman Edgar Wesley appeared in 64 games and compiled a .287 batting average and a .498 slugging percentage and led the team in both home runs (11) and RBIs (50).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Second baseman Frank Warfield also appeared in 64 games, led the team in plate appearances (296) and ranked second on the team in runs scored (49) and third in hits (71).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Infielder Joe Hewitt appeared in 54 games (22 at shortstop, 16 at second base, and 15 at third base).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] He had a .201 batting average he had almost as many walks (33) as hits (38), boosting his on-base percentage to .332.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] He also led the team's infielders with 159 assists.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Player-manager Pete Hill played in center field and appeared in 45 games.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] He compiled a .281 batting average and a team-leading 38 walks boosted his on-base percentage to .443.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Hill was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Bill Gatewood led the pitching staff with a 15–5 record and a 2.72 earned run average (ERA).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] He appeared in 24 games for the Stars, 16 as a starter, and had 11 complete games and 90 strikeouts in 159 innings pitched.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] Bill Holland led the team in games (28), starts (19), complete games (13), innings pitched (169), and strikeouts (96).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1920-detroit-stars-season] He compiled an 11–6 record and a 2.77 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The **1921 Bacharach Giants baseball team**, sometimes known as the **Atlantic City Bacharach Giants**, represented the Bacharach Giants as an independent during the 1921 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team compiled a 44–36–2 (.549) and was recognized as the Eastern independent champion of Negro league baseball.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] Dick Redding was the team's manager and pitcher.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team played its home games at Inlet Park in Atlantic City, New Jersey.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-bacharach-giants-season] The team's leading pitchers were Dick Redding (16–11, 3.17 ERA, 130 strikeouts) and Red Ryan (7–5, 2.39 ERA, 43 strikeouts).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-chicago-american-giants] The **1921 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-chicago-american-giants] The team compiled a 55–28–4 record (44–22–2 against NNL opponents) and won the NNL pennant.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] The **1921 Detroit Stars baseball team** competed in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1921 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] The Stars compiled a 38–46–1 record (.453) and finished fifth in the NNL.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Second baseman Frank Warfield appeared in 80 games and compiled a .264 batting average.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] He also tallied 38 walks, boosting his on-base percentage to .346.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] He led the team with 65 runs scored, 13 stolen bases, and six triples.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Shortstop Bill Riggins appeared in 80 games, compiled a .305 batting average, and led the team with 99 hits, 21 doubles, and 44 RBIs.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Player-manager Pete Hill played right field and appeared in 61 games.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] He led the team with a .337 batting average, .433 on-base percentage, .667 slugging percentage, 44 RBIs, six triples, and six times hit by pitch.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] First baseman Edgar Wesley appeared in 57 games and compiled a .318 batting average, .384 on-base percentage, and .514 slugging percentage.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Third baseman Johnson Hill and compiled a .278 batting average with 69 hits and 18 extra-base hits.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Catcher Bruce Petway appeared in 63 games and compiled a .301 batting average with 68 hits.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Bill Holland appeared in 31 games, 19 as a starter, and compiled a 13–12 record with a 3.45 earned run average (ERA).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Bill Force appeared in 33 games, 22 as a starter, and compiled a 12–10 record with a 3.94 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Bill Gatewood appeared in 21 games, 16 as a starter, compiled a 6–7 record, and led the team with a 2.97 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Gatewood also performed well at the plate, compiling a .333 batting average, .377 on-base percentage, and .474 slugging percentage.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1921-detroit-stars-season] Andy Cooper appeared in 27 games, 19 as a starter, and compiled a 6–9 record with a 4.65 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The **1932 Detroit Wolves baseball team** was a Negro league baseball team that competed in the East–West League (EWL) during the 1932 baseball season.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The team compiled a 28–9 (.757) record (26–5 (.839) against EWL opponents) and won the EWL pennant, finishing six-and-a-half games ahead of the second-place team.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The Wolves played their home games at Hamtramck Stadium in Hamtramck, Michigan.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The team included on its roster five players who were later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: center fielder Cool Papa Bell, first baseman Mule Suttles, shortstop Willie "The Devil" Wells, and pitchers Ray Brown and Smokey Joe Williams.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The teams winning percentage (.839) vs. teams in its league is the highest by a team in a season in the Negro Major Leagues.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] After the 1931 season, the Negro National League (NNL) disbanded.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The Detroit Stars, which had represented the City of Detroit in the NNL since 1920, were also disbanded at that time.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The Detroit Wolves were organized prior to the 1932 season as part of the newly formed East–West League (EWL).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Cumberland Posey was a leader behind the formation of the EWL and the owner of the Wolves.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Described by one sportswriter as "the smartest man in Negro baseball," he was posthumously inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Dizzy Dismukes, an Alabama native and right-handed pitcher, was hired as the team's manager.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] In an effort to build a roster, the Wolves signed players from the recently disbanded Negro National League.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] In particular, the Wolves signed seven players from the 1931 St.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Louis players were: Cool Papa Bell; Willie Wells; Mule Suttles; right fielder Quincy Trouppe; third baseman Dewey Creacy; and pitchers Ted Trent and Nate Hunter.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] In early June, the Wolves sent Suttles, John Henry Russell, and Creacy to the Homestead Grays in exchange for Giles (first baseman), Allen (second baseman), and Jud Wilson (third baseman).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The team featured a powerful lineup of batters, scoring an average of 5.5 runs per game against EWL opponents.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Center fielder Cool Papa Bell, a native of Mississippi, ranked second in the league with a .340 batting average and also ranked among the league's leaders with 40 runs scored (fourth) and nine stolen bases (tied for second).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Bell was one of the first Negro league players inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame, receiving the honor in 1974.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] First baseman Mule Suttles, an Alabama native, was the team's leading slugger and led the league with 48 RBIs and 22 doubles and ranked second in the league with 30 bases on balls and a .524 slugging percentage.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Suttles also led the EWL with 468 putouts.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Third baseman Dewey Creacy led the EWL by appearing in 63 games and playing 538 innings.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Creacy also led the league's third basemen with 72 putouts and 92 assists.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Shortstop Willie Wells, a Texas native, ranked first among the league's shortstops with 87 putouts and second with 111 assists.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Considered one of the best defensive shortstops of his era, Wells was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1997.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The Wolves' pitching staff compiled a 2.77 earned run average (ERA) that was the best in the EWL.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Bertrum Hunter, a right-handed pitcher from Arizona, led the league in both wins (10) and strikeouts (72).
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] He appeared in 16 games for the Wolves, 10 as a starter, and compiled a 10–2 record with a 2.93 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] William Bell, a right-handed pitcher from Texas, ranked second in the league with a 2.47 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Smokey Joe Williams, another right-hander from Texas, compiled a 5–1 record and a 2.72 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Williams was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1999.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] Ray Brown compiled a 7–7 record in 16 games with a 3.67 ERA.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] He went on to fame with the Homestead Grays and was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:1932-detroit-wolves-season/1932-detroit-wolves-season] The following players participated in games for the 1932 Detroit Wolves.
